  <character-development>
    Florence: Deception revealed. Initially defensive, then confesses. The advice she gave WAS good—her instincts are sound—but she hid behind Elder Twist's authority because she didn't believe her own voice would be valued. Now facing consequences: isolation from community, loss of trust. Beginning to realize she needs to earn respect through her actual contributions, not borrowed authority.

    Kira: Steps up to defend Florence despite betrayal. Can see past the deception to the value of Florence's actual insights. Growing into leadership role—mediating conflict, looking beyond surface issues. Less concerned with authority and procedures than plants are.

    Holloway: Deeply hurt by the deception. Just learned to trust their own judgment instead of external authority, and now discovers one of their own was creating false authority. Struggles with: how do we move forward when we can't trust each other?

    Runner: Feels personally betrayed—Runner's affection for the group makes dishonesty hurt more. Wants to trust but doesn't know how to rebuild it.

    Remedy: Philosophical about it—boundaries and identity crisis makes Remedy understand confusion between self and role. But still hurt by the lie.

    Plants collectively: Learning that trusting themselves includes dealing with internal deception. Not all threats are external.
